,"1377":"1377","1344":"1344","1453":"1453","1321":"1321","1320":"1320","about 1320":"about 1320","1328":"1328","Mochettes, Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire,England":"Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England","Fern Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Muschet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Norman, Scottish: locative name from Montfiquet (Calvados).","2  English: there has been some confusion with   Muskett  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mushett","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Mushet  ."]},{"name":"Muskett","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>mouschet</i>, <i>mousquet</i> ‘male (tercel) of a small hawk, especially a sparrowhawk’, from a diminutive of <i>mouche</i> ‘fly’."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":8,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":17,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir George Muschet was born about 1320, in Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England, his father, William IV Muschet Sheriff of Cambridge and Huntingdonshire, was 38 and his mother, Alice, was 41. He married Agnes in 1333, in Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England. He died in 1377, in his hometown, at the age of 58."},"et":{"about 1320–1377":"umbes 1320–1377","1320–1377":"1320–1377","1321–1341":"1321–1341","1344–1373":"1344–1373","1283–1362":"1283–1362","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1341":"1341","1362":"1362","1373":"1373","1283":"1283","1280":"1280","1337":"1337","1333":"1333","1377":"1377","1344":"1344","1453":"1453","1321":"1321","1320":"1320","about 1320":"umbes 1320","1328":"1328","Mochettes, Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire,England":"Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England","Fern Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1320–1377":"noin 1320–1377","1320–1377":"1320–1377","1321–1341":"1321–1341","1344–1373":"1344–1373","1283–1362":"1283–1362","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1341":"1341","1362":"1362","1373":